{"usCongressBioId":"M000663","familyName":"Merritt","givenName":"Schuyler","honorificPrefix":"Mr.","unaccentedFamilyName":"Merritt","unaccentedGivenName":"Schuyler","birthDate":"1853-12-16","birthCirca":false,"deathDate":"1953-04-01","deathCirca":false,"image":[{"contentUrl":"https://history.house.gov/Collection/Detail/25769818907","caption":"Collection of the U.S. House of Representatives <a href=\"https://history.house.gov/Collection/Detail/25769818907\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">About this object</a>"}],"profileText":"A Representative from Connecticut; born in New York City, December 16, 1853; moved with his parents to Stamford, Conn., in 1855; prepared for college at private schools in that city; was graduated from Yale College, New Haven, Conn., in 1873, and from Columbia Law School, New York City, in 1876; interested in the manufacture of locks and keys and also engaged in banking 1877-1917; member of the Connecticut constitutional convention in 1904; member of the State board of education 1910-1916; delegate to the Republican National Convention in 1916; elected as a Republican to the Sixty-fifth Congress to fill the vacancy caused by the death of Ebenezer J. Hill; reelected to the Sixty-sixth and to the five succeeding Congresses and served from November 6, 1917, to March 3, 1931; unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1930; again elected to the Seventy-third and Seventy-fourth Congresses (March 4, 1933-January 3, 1937); unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1936 to the Seventy-fifth Congress; continued his interests in the Yale &amp; Towne Manufacturing Co. and the First Stamford National Bank; died in Stamford, Conn., April 1, 1953; interment in Woodland Cemetery.","relationship":[],"jobPositions":[{"job":{"name":"Representative","jobType":"CongressMemberJob"},"startDate":"1923-03-04","startCirca":false,"congressAffiliation":{"congress":{"name":"The 68th United States Congress","congressNumber":68,"congressType":"USCongress","startDate":"1923